Tyrianthina„ a colour produced by the combination of two different processes of dyeing. The wool was first dyed violet, by dipping in a mixture of the black purple dye—-a variety of the dye procured from the purple fish, purpura pelayia—and the red of the murex or buccinum. It was then subjected to the Tyrian purple proceSS, that is, twice dipped‚ first in pelagium, the dye procured from the pezayia, prepared in a special way, and then in the inice of the buccinum. This latter, the purple so often mentioned, was produced also in Greece, (Sparta especially) and in Asia Minor, but the Tyrian was reckoned the best.
